  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Upon Visiting Deseong Castle
  author: Lim Yu-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The courtyard rests in silence—autumn clouds drift pale and clear.
    The city lies empty—night's moon shines pristine and bright.
    Sand ripples and churns—its traces shimmer like waves.
    The distant mountains glow—their fires burn like lanterns in the dark.
    Wine matures to sweetness—thoughts of talented poets arise.
    A poem composed—sent onward to the mountain monks.
    Few are the old friends—in this far corner of heaven.
    Who might lean with me—upon this lofty pavilion's rail?
  footnotes:
    - The poet weaves together lines and couplets from various celebrated Tang poets (Zhiyuan, Li Dong, Zhang Hu, Li Shizhong, Qian Qi, and Du Fu), a sophisticated compositional technique that demonstrates both erudition and homage to the poetic tradition.
    - The progression moves from natural observation to human reflection, culminating in a meditation on solitude and the absence of kindred spirits—a common theme in classical East Asian poetry.
    - Deseong Castle (德城) likely refers to a historical fortress or watchtower, serving as the concrete setting for this more abstract meditation on poetry, friendship, and the passage of time.
